social_posts.post_text: Soft winter light in a cold garage. 😍
the first few layers 💙

Daytime activity in my studio has come nearly to a standstill but I’m able to escape here in the evenings. A welcomed change of pace in these dreary winter months. Without natural daylight I’m less tempted to get distracted fumbling around documenting and photographing too so I just paint! 

Therefore I’ll share some photos I’ve had stored away. It’s fun to get these out into the world in some way. 

/ my handmade red ochre watercolor on @shizenpaper

January projects; I started a toucan! I’m using some old National Geographics to reference for practice drawings - they’re so fun to look through, I knit a few coasters and one of them ended up being a great eraser flake eraser - if that made any sense at all haha, and I’m leaning into making some indigo half pans for a later idea. Those floral paper cutouts (not stickers) were a pure and simple impulse buy from Hobby Lobby. I just loved them and we’ll use them for my daughters valentines this year most likely. They’re so cute!! Its’s such a unique item to sell but if there were any floral artists out there that made these I would totally use them for handmade greeting cards!!

I love this image taken by the @shopcanvas.co team when they visited me last November. Indigo has become a staple in my watercolor arsenal. I have nearly abandoned all my ultramarine hues…. It’s beyond beautiful to work with and incredibly lightfast. 

Thank you for the images Canvas!

Garage light on a little landscape paint-sketch. The ochre washes used for under paintings of oil paintings have always dazzled me. A raw beauty full of potential. I’ve always thought they could be beautiful on their own somehow. 🧡
A beautiful day in February I don’t want to forget. 🧡

Seeing this color in fun ways this week - I also made a watercolor rose!! Thank you @kaitlinroseslattery for bringing me these pigments from France. Preserving them in these vintage Prang watercolor tins was a last minute decision but I love it!!! I’ll put a sister rose next to this one, likely the yellow ochre. 😍

My time in my studio the past six months has been so much less than anticipated over the last six months. It’s been replaced with some pretty irreplaceable memories with my babies though. I told myself to just *try* to tackle something in here even if it was just looking at things and I succeeded in that. I’ve felt so much more secure in what I love doing & letting other ideas go. Even *investing* in artists I felt really drawn to, relabeling what could have just stayed as jealousy as support and doing my part in giving them the love I’ve felt from my community. This community. Grateful to still be here! More to come. ☀️🙏🏻

The month of February brought watercolor roses into my life. Each of them are about 5ml of paint (almost two full pans!). I’m intrigued to see how many different hues I’ll get from my white rose. I had the plan of making it pure white but I didn’t want to waste the red ochre I had already poured inside. I LOVE it! It will live on my marble slab until it’s completely gone. 🥰 The watercolor pans inside the lid on the bottom left we’re the original paints that came with the vintage tins. See the highlight to learn the story behind them!

Gaining ground with some of these paintings. I really couldn’t have ever guessed that working monochrome with watercolor could be this vibrant, pigment heavy and full of texture. Cannot get enough of these. 😍

Attention is the beginning of devotion. - Mary Oliver

I finished Four Thousand Weeks this week. This mentioned quote has been my brain bubble gum, stirring a lot of different thoughts and inspiring me steer my face and thoughts more towards things I want to be devoted to.  This spring has felt so magical already too and I’m grateful to continue my work on these little landscapes in some of this warmer weather. ☀️ 🌞 ⛅️

I made myself work on some Appalachian landscapes since I’ve been stuck on deserts for some time now, just to give me a little range. My line & shadow work has room to grow but I’m loving these colors and materials. I have a lot of #drawing ahead of me this year. 🙏🏻
So many little works in progress! It’s been a cold spring but our heater is doing it’s job keeping my space warm. 🙏🏻

HI INSTAGRAM! I miss my friends here… I’m quietly working on these and it’s been nearly a year, the slowest I’ve ever worked but the happiest pace. There’s over 40 of these little watercolors so far! I’ll be working on developing these into prints this year. I’ve also been crushing through @bemapodcast and loving getting lost in the Old Testament - hearing it dissected through an eastern perspective has been so enlightening. I’m not sure if this post will get visibility so if you’re here HELLO TO YOU!! 👋🏻🙌🏻
my little time capsule of may + june so far 🥰

a landslide - foraged watercolor on forgotten brand of watercolor paper; uncertain on dimensions as well (5x5?) 

I think this is one of my favorites so far.
There’s an hour in the afternoon that the sun hits my table at this angle and I love working under it. ❤️‍🔥

I’ve been feeling a strong nudge to return here again the past couple weeks. ✨ I’ll be cleaning up my studio (it’s been used as a Christmas gift wrapping station since November) & glad to see it return to life.  It’s been a year and a half, maybe even closer to two years since I decided to take a break and I’m ready to incorporate this part of my life back into my routine. I’m intrigued to see what the Lord is doing this time around. 🌒

I’m a week or so tardy for a 2023 recap! I only took a dozen videos or so but I feel good about what I accomplished! We enjoyed so much quality family time together and much to my (genuine) surprise I was able to collect *stunning* scans of my paintings. I doubted from the moment it was mentioned thinking the scans wouldn’t really capture the color well but I was wrong! We’re working on finding the best route for prints so that’s next on the horizon! Until then I’ll continue to get this place ready for spring and summer. 🥰
